<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-307-314  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 307 314.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 20 1989 v3 n12 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Crime net plan loses on-line tracking.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Casatelli, Christine; Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FBI has agreed to eliminate an on-line suspect trackingfeature in the upgrade of the National Crime Information Center(NCIC) system upgrade.andP;  The on-line tracking feature would gatherinformation for an electronic dossier in a remote agency on asuspect's whereabouts every time the subject was stopped for aroutine check.andP;  The network, dubbed NCIC 2000, will be linked tofive other agencies.andP;  The outside links may make system securityand data integrity difficult to maintain.andP;  The NCIC receives750,000 inquiries per day from law enforcement agencies on alllevels, and NCIC stores 20 million records on missing persons andstolen property.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationUnited States. National Crime Information CenterLaw EnforcementInformation SystemsOn-LineData Security.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>